Unsupervised Learning: Trade&Ahead¶

Context¶

The stock market has consistently proven to be a good place to invest in and save for the future. There are a lot of compelling reasons to invest in stocks. It can help in fighting inflation, create wealth, and also provides some tax benefits. Good steady returns on investments over a long period of time can also grow a lot more than seems possible. Also, thanks to the power of compound interest, the earlier one starts investing, the larger the corpus one can have for retirement. Overall, investing in stocks can help meet life's financial aspirations.

It is important to maintain a diversified portfolio when investing in stocks in order to maximise earnings under any market condition. Having a diversified portfolio tends to yield higher returns and face lower risk by tempering potential losses when the market is down. It is often easy to get lost in a sea of financial metrics to analyze while determining the worth of a stock, and doing the same for a multitude of stocks to identify the right picks for an individual can be a tedious task. By doing a cluster analysis, one can identify stocks that exhibit similar characteristics and ones which exhibit minimum correlation. This will help investors better analyze stocks across different market segments and help protect against risks that could make the portfolio vulnerable to losses.

Objective¶

Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy firm who provide their customers with personalized investment strategies. They have hired you as a Data Scientist and provided you with data comprising stock price and some financial indicators for a few companies listed under the New York Stock Exchange. They have assigned you the tasks of analyzing the data, grouping the stocks based on the attributes provided, and sharing insights about the characteristics of each group.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: An abbreviation used to uniquely identify publicly traded shares of a particular stock on a particular stock market
  • Security: Name of the company
  • GICS Sector: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • GICS Sub Industry: The specific sub-industry group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • Current Price: Current stock price in dollars
  • Price Change: Percentage change in the stock price in 13 weeks
  • Volatility: Standard deviation of the stock price over the past 13 weeks
  • ROE: A measure of financial performance calculated by dividing net income by shareholders' equity (shareholders' equity is equal to a company's assets minus its debt)
  • Cash Ratio: The ratio of a company's total reserves of cash and cash equivalents to its total current liabilities
  • Net Cash Flow: The difference between a company's cash inflows and outflows (in dollars)
  • Net Income: Revenues minus expenses, interest, and taxes (in dollars)
  • Earnings Per Share: Company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding (in dollars)
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company's stock currently held by all its shareholders
  • P/E Ratio: Ratio of the company's current stock price to the earnings per share
  • P/B Ratio: Ratio of the company's stock price per share by its book value per share (book value of a company is the net difference between the company's total assets and total liabilities)

Observations:¶

  • The stock price has a very large variability, ranging from 4.5 USD to ~ 1275 USD, with a std more than 20% larger than the mean. The distribution of the stock price is heavilty right-skewed, as the maximum is much larger than the median and the mean.
  • The price change ranges from ~ -47% to ~ 55%, indicating that some companies have gained value and some have lost value in the past quarter. The mean and median are at 4.08% and 4.82%, respectively, showing that the market as a whole has somewhat grown in this timeframe.
  • The median and mean of volatility in the past quarter are at 1.39 and 1.53, respectively, which are anticipated numbers for this index, showing that the market hasn't been too volatile, but the maximum value of this parameter is ~ 4.5, indicating higher degrees of volatility for some companies.
  • The median ROE is 15, revealing that the net incomes of 50% of companies are at least 15 times more than their assests (minus their debts). There are substantial differences between the maximum ROE and its measures of central tendency, showing the right-skewedness of this variable.
  • The minimum value of the cash ratio is zero, suggesting that some companies have no cash reserve, but some well-performing company has a cash reserve more than 950 times larger than its liabilities. The median and mean cash ratio are at 47 and ~ 70, respectively, again, showing a right-skewed distribution.
  • The median net cash flow is about \$2M, indicating that more than 50% of companies have a positive cash flow of 2M USD or more. The average net cash flow of companies is about 55M USD, but there is a company whose cash burn rate is much higher than its cash inflow and, as a result, has a net cash flow below -11B USD!! Some high-earning company (or a company with strong fundraising), on the other hand, has a net cash flow above 20B USD.
  • The average net income of companies is about 1.5B USD, and more that 50% of them have a net income of 0.7B USD or larger. On both extremes, there are some very poorly-performing losing billions of dollars and some very successful ones with net incomes above $20B.
  • For at least 50% of companies, the ratio of net profit to outstanding shares is more that 2.89, i.e. an investor can earn about \$2.89 per share. For some highly profitable company this ratio is more than 50, and for some seriusly failing company earnings per share is less than -60.
  • The median and average estimated shares outstanding for the listed companies are about 310M and 577M, while there is a small-sized company with only around 28 million outstanding shares, and some giant company with more than 6.15 billion outstanding shares.
  • The P/E ratio exhibits a very high variability, with its std being nearly 36% larger than the mean. The mean P/E ratio is ~ 33, i.e, on average, the market has put a value 33 larger than companies' earnings per share on their stocks. There are also companies, whose P/E ratio is in the order of hundreds, indicating the right-skewedness of this attribute, but also the potentially overvalued stock prices of these companies or their expected rapid growth.
  • The median P/B ratio is below zero, indicating that most companies have a negative book value, or, more liabilities than assets. Less than 25% of companies have a P/B ratio greater than 4, and the maximum P/B ratio for the listed companies is about 129. A company with a very large P/B ratio has most likely already done its growth, and perhaps isn't a good future investment.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

In the following EDA, we will aim to direct the EDA so that the questions asked below are adressed, but the EDA will be far more comprehensive than merely answering the leading questions.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of stock prices look like?
  2. The stocks of which economic sector have seen the maximum price increase on average?
  3. How are the different variables correlated with each other?
  4. Cash ratio provides a measure of a company's ability to cover its short-term obligations using only cash and cash equivalents. How does the average cash ratio vary across economic sectors?
  5. P/E ratios can help determine the relative value of a company's shares as they signify the amount of money an investor is willing to invest in a single share of a company per dollar of its earnings. How does the P/E ratio vary, on average, across economic sectors?
In [12]:
# Auxiliary function for annotating the bars in a countplot
def countplot_labeling(cntplt, data, perc = True, decimal = 1):
  ''' This function gets a countplot and the dataset that has generated
  the plot to produce the values corresponding to each bar (category).
  If perc = True, percentages will be shown.'''

  from math import isnan

  total = data.shape[0]  # total number of values in the dataset
  for p in cntplt.patches:
        height_val = float(p.get_height())
        if(isnan(height_val)):
          height_val = 0
        if(abs(height_val - round(height_val)) < 1e-6):
          height_val = int(height_val)  
        if perc == True:
          # percentage of each category
          label = "{:.1f}%".format(100*height_val/total)
        else:
          label = "{}".format(round(height_val,decimal))  # count of each category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        if(height_val == 0):
          label = '0'

        # annotate the bar
        cntplt.annotate(label, (x, y), ha = "center", va = "center", size = 12, xytext = (0, 5), textcoords = "offset points")

Bivariate Analysis¶

The given dataset consists of several columns, making the number of possible bivariate analyses quite large. Therefore, we limit our bivariate analysis to the understanding of the relationships between some of the most important variables, while being guided by the leading questions.

Heatmap of Correlation Coefficients

In [27]:
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 10));
sns.heatmap(data = df.corr(), fmt = '.2f', annot = True, cmap = 'seismic', cbar = False,
            vmin = -1, vmax = 1);

Observations:¶

  • More than any other factor, the stock price of a company is correlated with its earnings per share, that is the profit the company makes (per share).
  • Volatility index and the percentage of price change have a sizeable negative correlation, i.e., companies with declining stock prices have higher volatility.
  • Volaitility is also negatively correlated with net income and earnings per share, i.e., companies with a better monetary stance (higher incomes and profits) have a steadier stock price.
  • Oddly, the correlation table shows that companies with higher ROEs have lower net incomes and earnings per share. This might have been caused by outliers, or companies with small assets and large debts, for which the denominator of the ROE becomes small.
  • Companies with higher ratios of cash reserves to liabilities tend to have higher P/B ratios. Note that lower liabilities mean than the book value per share which appears in the denominator of the P/B ratio can remain above zero, yielding a positive value for the P/B ratio.
  • Net cash flow and cash ratio appear to have a small positive correlation. Naturally, companies with a positive flow of cash are also expected to have larger cash reserves, and thus larger cash ratios.
  • Companies with large profits are also expected to have higher incomes, explaining the large positive correlation between earnings per share and net income.
  • Companies with higher net incomes tend to have higher outstanding shares. This makes sense as a major source of revenue (income) for a company is public sale of its stocks, therefore increasing the number of shares outstanding.

Data Preprocessing¶

  • Missing value treatment: No missing values were detected in the EDA section, so this step won't be necessary.
  • Outlier check: We take a closer look at the distributions of numerical variables to determine whether the treatment of outliers will be crucial before clustering or whether any of outliers are irregular and odd.
  • Scaling: Since the units and ranges of variables are significantly different from one another, transforming them so that they all fall within the same range and order of magnitude is vital prior to any distance-based clustering. We will use standard scaling (removing the mean of all numerical attributes and dividing the result by their corresponding standard deviations) to achieve this goal.

K-Means Clustering¶

Elbow Plot¶

In [35]:
# Setting the range of no. of clusters
no_clusters = np.arange(1, 11)
# Defining within-cluster summ of squares array
WCSS = np.zeros(len(no_clusters))

# Looping over no. of clusters to calculate the WCSS for each 
for k in no_clusters:
    clust_model = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 1)
    segments = clust_model.fit_predict(df_model_scaled)
    WCSS[k-1] = np.sum(np.min(np.square(cdist(df_model_scaled, clust_model.cluster_centers_)), axis = 1))/df.shape[0]

# Plotting WCSS vs. k
plt.figure(figsize = (8.6, 5));
plt.plot(no_clusters, WCSS, color = 'blue', marker = 'o');
plt.xlabel('k');
plt.ylabel('Normalized WCSS');
plt.xticks(ticks = no_clusters);
plt.title('Variation of the Within-Cluster Sum of Squares with No. of Clusters');

# Defining the silhouette scores array
sil_scores = np.zeros(len(no_clusters)-1)

# Looping over no. of clusters to calculate the average silhouette score of each
for k in no_clusters[1:]:
    clust_model = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 1)
    segments = clust_model.fit_predict(df_model_scaled)
    sil_scores[k-2] = silhouette_score(df_model_scaled, clust_model.labels_)

Observations:¶

  • Note that in our elbow plot we demonstrate the whitine cluster sum of squares, which is identical to what yellowbrick's KElbowVisualizer() does, except in our plot, the results are normalized by the number of data points.
  • Although neither our elbow plot nor that generated by the yellowbrick's method reveal a clear-cut elbow, but according to both the most visible elbow appears somewhere around k = 4. Therefore, k = 3 and 4 seem to be the best candidates for the number of clusters, and good compromises between compression and accuracy.
  • As can be seen, the average silhouette score is maximized at k = 3. Furthermore, according to the silhouette score distribution plots, adding an extra cluster and setting k = 4, will create a new cluster 3, most data points of which have negative silhouette scores, indicating that that they're closer to another cluster, which implies that this new class is artificial. Therfore, we choose to set k = 4 while building the final k-means clustering model.

Final Model¶

In [42]:
# Copying the scaled data into a new dataframe to ensure it remains untouched for the rest of calculations
df_kmeans_scaled = df_model_scaled.copy()
# Implementing the final k-means clustering using the optimal value of k
t_i = time()
kmeans_final_model = KMeans(n_clusters = 3, random_state = 1)
kmeans_segments = kmeans_final_model.fit_predict(df_model_scaled)
t_e = time()
print('The execution of k-means algorithm takes {} seconds.'.format(round(t_e - t_i, 4)))
# Adding the clusters introduced by k-means model to the dataframes
df_kmeans_scaled['Segment'] = kmeans_segments
df_model['K-Means Segment'] = kmeans_segments

The execution of k-means algorithm takes 0.0482 seconds.

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Impact of Distance Metric and Linkage Method¶

Cophenetic Correlation

In [49]:
# Linkage methods applicable with all distance metrics
common_link_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted']
# Linkage and distance hyperparameters passed to linkage()
# Note that 'centroid' and 'ward' are only compatible with Euclidean distance measure
linkage_hyperparams = {'cityblock': common_link_methods, 'chebyshev': common_link_methods,
                       'Mahalanobis': common_link_methods, 'euclidean': common_link_methods + ['centroid', 'ward']}
# A dataframe of cophenetic correlations for all possible pairs of linkage methods and distance metrics
cc_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Linkage Method', 'Distance Metric', 'Cophenetic Correlation'])

idx = 0 # A counter for indices of dataframe
for distance_metric in linkage_hyperparams.keys():
    for linkage_method in linkage_hyperparams[distance_metric]:
      # Implementing linkage method for a certain combination of linkage methods & distance metrics
      Z = linkage(df_model_scaled, metric = distance_metric, method = linkage_method, 
                  optimal_ordering = True)
      # Calculating cophenetic correlation
      cc, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_model_scaled, metric = distance_metric))
      del coph_dists
      cc_df.loc[idx, :] = [linkage_method.capitalize(), distance_metric.capitalize(), cc]
      idx += 1
# Sorting the results from the highest coph. correlation to the lowest
cc_df.sort_values(by = 'Cophenetic Correlation', ascending = False)

Observations:¶

  • Here, we use optimal ordering while calling linkage(). However, adopting this method somewhat slows down the process, it helps demonstrate the leaves and clusters of an HC model more visibly, when visualizing its dendrogram. Note that the only effect of optimal ordering is on visualization, and it doesn't impact the results of clustering in any other ways.
  • To keep the comparison between the initial spatial distance of two data points and their dendrogramic distance fair and reasonable, we ensured that the distance metric in the linkage() and pdist() functions are identical.
  • In the next step, we visualize the dendrogram of the top five models with highest cophenetic correlations along with when linkage method is set as 'ward'. It's been shown that Ward's method is highly skilled in rendering distinct and well-separated clusters, and perhaps for this reason, it's also selected as the default linkage method of Agglomerative Clustering.

Observations:¶

  • As we'd suspected earlier, adopting Ward's method for the linkage of leaves (sub-clusters) in an HC model, despite not having the highest cophenetic correlation, yields far more meaningful, interpretable, distinct and well-separated clusters, in comparison with all other models. Regardless, the cophenetic correlation coefficient of the model provided by Ward's method is still fairly good and above 0.7.
  • We thus use Euclidean as the distanc metric and Ward's method as the linkage method, while building the final HC model. As mentioned before, Ward's method only works with the Euclidean measure.

Silhouette Scores

In [56]:
# Defining silhouette scores array
sil_scores = np.zeros(len(no_clusters)-1)

# Looping over no. of clusters to calculate the average silhouette score of each
for k in no_clusters[1:]:
    clust_model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = k, affinity = 'euclidean', linkage = 'ward')
    segments = clust_model.fit_predict(df_model_scaled)
    sil_scores[k-2] = silhouette_score(df_model_scaled, clust_model.labels_)

# Plotting mean distortions vs. k
plt.figure(figsize = (8.4, 5));
plt.plot(no_clusters[1:], sil_scores, color = 'blue', marker = 'o');
plt.xlabel('k');
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score');
plt.title('Variation of the Silhouette Score with No. of Clusters (HC Model)');

Observations:¶

For the given linkage method and distance metric, k = 4 results in the highest silhouette score. Four clusters also look fairly good on the dendrogram plot. Therefore, we'll set the number of clusters in our HC model as 4.

Final Model¶

In [57]:
# Copying the scaled data into a new dataframe to ensure it remains untouched for the rest of calculations
df_hc_scaled = df_model_scaled.copy()
# Implementing the final hierarchical clustering using the 'best' linkage method & distance metric
t_i = time()
HC_final_model = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = 4, affinity = 'euclidean', linkage = 'ward')
HC_segments = HC_final_model.fit_predict(df_model_scaled)
t_e = time()
print('The execution of hierarchical clustering takes {} seconds.'.format(round(t_e - t_i, 4)))
# Adding the clusters introduced by k-means model to the dataframes
df_hc_scaled['Segment'] = HC_segments
df_model['HC Segment'] = HC_segments

The execution of hierarchical clustering takes 0.0093 seconds.

Observations:¶

  • Cluster 0 consists of struggling companies with negative recent price change and high-volatility stock prices. The average net income, net cash flow and earnings per share of this cluster is also below zero, suggesting that most companies in this cluster are suffering huge losses. The fairly high P/E ratio of this cluster can also indicate that stocks of this cluster are on average overvalued.
  • Cluster 1 is made up of highly profitable companies (the largest earnings per share, cash ratios and highest stock prices) with a fairly strong net cash flow and a decdent net income. These companies have also experience the largest price rise compared to those in the other clusters. The somewhat low value of shares outstanding may indicate these are perhaps mid-sized and rapidly growing businesses. The very high P/E and P/B ratios also imply that the stocks of this cluster are most likely overvalued and past their peak prices. This cluster is the only one with a positive P/B ratio, suggesting that only the companies in this cluster, on average, have more total assets than liabilities.
  • Cluster 2 represents giant corporates with very large net cash flows, net incomes and shares outstanding. However the stock prices of this cluster is lower than the other three, but, on average, companies in this cluster have decent price rises, fairly good eranings per share, reasonable P/E ratios and low volatility indices, meaning that someone investing in these companies can expect a reliable and steadily growing source of income.
  • The overwhelming majority of companies (84%) fall in cluster 3. The average stock price of this cluster is moderate (only lower than cluster 1), and it also has a fairly high earnings per share (again, second to cluster 1). The cash flow of this cluster is positive, but much lower than those of cluster 1 and 2. Its net income also falls somewhere between cluster 1 and 2. The volatility and P/E ratio of this cluster are moderate, indicating that its stock prices are fairly reliable. This cluster includes the biggest bulk of companies, so, unsurprisngly, most properties of this cluster are modest and somewhere in the middle.

Observations:¶

  • Cluster 0, which was characterized by declining stock prices and high volatility, is predictably dominated by Energy companies, which also have these two properties.
  • Cluster 1, which consists of rapidly growing and highly prosperous businesses, is unsurprisingly filled with big names in IT (e.g., Netflix and Amazon) and pharmaceutical (e.g., Regeneron and Alexion) industries. We remark that, in recent years, both sectors have experienced phenomenal growth.
  • Cluster 2 represents internationally-recognized, massive corporations, with really large net cash flows and net incomes. Therefore, it is not surprising to see several prominent financial institutions (e.g., Bank of America, Citigroup and JPMorgan Chase) present in this cluster.
  • Cluster 3 describes average (moderately successful) performance, so, expectedly, the majority of companies from all sectors (except Energy and Telecommunications) reside in this cluster.

Observations:¶

  • Cluster 0:
    • Low stock price and negative price change.
    • Highest volatility index.
    • Highest ROE but the lowest cash ratio and negative average net cash flow and income. The high ROE doesn't necessarily translate to high net income and profitability, as it could've been caused by low available assets and high debts.
    • Very high P/E ratio, indicating that many stocks in this cluster are most likely overvalued.
  • Cluster 1:
    • The highest current stock price and price rise.
    • Moderate volatility.
    • Highest cash ratio and earnings per share, as well as the second highest net cash flow.
    • Very high P/E and P/B ratios, signaling that stocks of this cluster are very possibly overvalued.
    • The cluster is primarily made up of thriving IT and Biotech companies.
  • Cluster 2:
    • Lowest average stock price, but very decent price increase with the lowest volatility index, making the price and its steady growth reliable.
    • Fairly high cash ratio, with the highest net cash flow and net income.
    • A decent average earnings per share with a reasonable (low) P/E ratio.
    • The highest estimated shares outstanding can be understood by the fact that this cluster mainly contains very large corporations.
  • Cluster 3:
    • Moderate current stock price with a moderate price rise and a fairly low volatility.
    • Moderate cash ratio with a fairly low but positive net cash flow.
    • Positive net income but much lower than the average income of cluster 0.
    • Moderate earnings per share, with a reasonable mean P/E ratio.
    • Much larger count of companies compared to the other three clusters.
    • The cluster mainly consists of companies with an acceptable but modest financial performance, making most of its properties average and somewhere in the middle (compared to the rest of the clusters).

Silhouette score of the final k-means model: 0.464
Silhouette score of the final HC model: 0.465

Responses:

  • Both methods took only in the order of hundredth of a second, but we should note that the dataset of this project is small. When a very large dataset is dealt with, hierarchical clustering is expected to take much longer, since its execution time scales with the square of the number of data points, whereas that of k-means algorithm scales linearly.
  • The optimal numbers of clusters for the k-means and HC models were found to be equal to 3 and 4, respectively.
  • The silhouette score of both models are very close to each other, i.e. both models, on average, have done a similar job in placing the data points in the proper (closest) cluster.
  • The cluster pertaining to the highly prosperous IT and Biotech companies (cluster 1) detected by the HC model went fully unnoticed by the k-means algorithm, i.e. the HC model performed better in identifying more distinct and meaningful clusters. Most observations in cluster 1 of the HC model are placed in cluster 2 (average performance) by the k-means algorithm.

  • With the exception of the thriving tech companies neglected by the k-means model, both clustering techniques identified very similar and analogous clusters:

    1. High-volatility stocks with declining prices (mostly from the Energy sector): Cluster 1 of the k-means model and cluster 0 of the HC model.
    2. Giant and internationally prominent corporations with very large net incomes, cash flows and shares outstanding: Cluster 0 of the k-means model and cluster 2 of the HC model.
    3. Companies with an average performance, whose price rise, net income and cash flow are fairly moderate: Cluster 2 of the k-means model and cluster 3 of the HC model. This cluster makes the bulk of the dataset.

  • The number of observations in the main three clusters discussed above are also fairly similar between the two models, but, evidently, since the HC model has one additional cluster, fewer data points fall in the three primary clusters. The table below describes the distribution of the data points among these three clusters for both models.

  • Despite all similarities between the cluster 1 of k-means model and the cluster 0 of the HC model, both corresponding to struggling companies, which mostly come from the Energy sector, the net cash flow of the latter is negative, while that of the former is positive. This might have been caused by some outliers and/or incongruent data points falling in the cluster 1 of the k-means model.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Key observations:

  • We leveraged k-means algorithm and hierarchical clustering to group the stock data of a few hundred companies into informative and interpretable clusters from business point of view. Three primary clusters (struggling companies (mostly from the energy sector), giant corporations and companies with modest performance) emerged from both techniques. On additional cluster, pertaining to thriving biotech and IT companies, lacking in the k-means model, was also identified by the HC model.
  • The dataset consisted of the stock information of 340 NYSE companies, distributed in 11 economic sectors and 104 sub-industries, with the Industrials sector and the O&G Exploration & Production sub-industry being the most frequent classes, respectively. Since there are too many sub-industries, some with only a few data points, only the effect of economic sector on financial (stock) performance and clustering was analyzed.
  • Both models revealed similar silhouette scores and execution times. The latter won't hold for much larger datasets, as hierarchical clustering scales with the square of the number of observations, whereas k-means algorithm scales linearly, creating an inevitable and huge gap between their execution times when massive datasets are dealt with.
  • Among all numerical variables, stock price has the strongest correlation with earnings per share. The latter is highly and positively correlated with net income.
  • High volatility usually translates to declining stock prices.
  • The largest price increase and decrease have occured for the Healthcare and Energy sectors, respectively. The latter is also the most volatile sector, while Utilities sector shows to have the most steady stock prices.

Business insights:

  • At the moment, the Energy sector seems the most precarious one for investment, with big losses and high volatility.
  • Giant corporations, especially mammoth and internationally prominent financial institutions, appear to be the safest choice for investment. Although their price increase may not be as big as other business groups, but their low volatility and reasonable P/E ratio suggest a steady and reliable growth.
  • Presently, the entrepreneurial Biotech and IT firms exhibit phenomenal growth with high eranings per share and large sums of cash available. Although one should be wary of their high P/E and P/B ratios.
  • Overall, one should be careful not to be deceived by the current high stock price of some companies or their recent rapid growth and price increase. In order to have a smart investment and not to be surprised by an upcoming price dip, one should also take other factors such as a company's P/E and P/B ratios as well as its liabilities and debts into consideration.

Recommendations for future ML-based modeling:

  • Treatment of outliers doesn't appear to be a good idea, at least in this project, as it can lead to the elimination of clusters pertaining to excellent or terribly poor performance.
  • Addition of more observations to the dataset might enable us to have a more fair and balanced view of sectors and industries, which currently have only a few data points.
  • The optimal number of clusters shows to be somewhat subjective and dependent on domain knowledge, especially when carrying out k-means clustering, therefore consulting a domain expert in choosing a reasonable number for k is highly recommended, to ensure all generated clusters are meaningful and interpretable. Nonetheless, a legitimate piece of advice is that going for more and more clusters isn't always a good idea, as it may lead to the introduction of unnecessary, overlapping and artificial clusters.
